 and then we're living in a simulation.

46:11.560 --> 46:14.040
 So, okay, sorry for that tangent.

46:14.040 --> 46:16.000
 So that's the defining,

46:16.000 --> 46:19.640
 the distinction between computation and communication.

46:19.640 --> 46:22.000
 Let me say one more thing just to clarify,

46:22.000 --> 46:27.000
 communication ideally does not change the information.

46:27.160 --> 46:28.960
 It moves it from one place to another,

46:28.960 --> 46:30.960
 but it is preserved.

46:30.960 --> 46:32.560
 Got it, okay.

46:32.560 --> 46:33.760
 All right, that's beautiful.

46:33.760 --> 46:38.640
 So then the electron versus light distinction

46:38.640 --> 46:42.400
 and why are electrons good at computation

46:42.400 --> 46:44.560
 and light good at communication?

46:44.560 --> 46:48.840
 Yes, this is, there's a lot that goes into it, I guess,

46:48.840 --> 46:51.720
 but just try to speak to the simplest part of it.

46:54.120 --> 46:57.040
 Electrons interact strongly with one another.

46:57.040 --> 46:58.400
 They're charged particles.

46:58.400 --> 47:02.040
 So if I pile a bunch of them over here,

47:02.040 --> 47:03.880
 they're feeling a certain amount of force

47:03.880 --> 47:05.680
 and they wanna move somewhere else.

47:05.680 --> 47:06.920
 They're strongly interactive.

47:06.920 --> 47:08.920
 You can also get them to sit still.

47:08.920 --> 47:10.680
 You can, an electron has a mass,

47:10.680 --> 47:15.680
 so you can cause it to be spatially localized.

47:15.880 --> 47:18.120
 So for computation, that's useful

47:18.120 --> 47:20.160
 because now I can make these little devices

47:20.160 --> 47:21.960
 that put a bunch of electrons over here

47:21.960 --> 47:25.640
 and then I change the state of a gate,

47:25.640 --> 47:26.480
 like I've been describing,

47:26.480 --> 47:28.400
 put a different voltage on this gate

47:28.400 --> 47:30.000
 and now I move the electrons over here.

47:30.000 --> 47:31.240
 Now they're sitting somewhere else.

47:31.240 --> 47:34.000
 I have a physical mechanism

47:34.000 --> 47:36.080
 with which I can represent information.

47:36.080 --> 47:37.400
 It's spatially localized

47:37.400 --> 47:39.080
 and I have knobs that I can adjust

47:39.080 --> 47:42.440
 to change where those electrons are or what they're doing.

47:42.440 --> 47:46.000
 Light by contrast, photons of light,

47:46.000 --> 47:48.160
 which are the discrete packets of energy

47:48.160 --> 47:50.840
 that were identified by Einstein,

47:50.840 --> 47:53.560
 they do not interact with each other,

47:54.640 --> 47:56.320
 especially at low light levels.

47:56.320 --> 47:57.440
 If you're in a medium

47:57.440 --> 48:00.440
 and you have a bright, high light level,

48:00.440 --> 48:02.600
 you can get them to interact with each other

48:02.600 --> 48:05.400
 through the interaction with that medium that they're in,

48:05.400 --> 48:07.880
 but that's a little bit more exotic

48:07.880 --> 48:10.400
 and for the purposes of this conversation,

48:10.400 --> 48:13.280
 we can assume that photons don't interact with each other.

48:13.280 --> 48:16.160
 So if you have a bunch of them

48:16.160 --> 48:17.640
 all propagating in the same direction,

48:17.640 --> 48:19.200
 they don't interfere with each other.

48:19.200 --> 48:23.000
 If I wanna send, if I have a communication channel

48:23.000 --> 48:24.520
 and I put one more photon on it,

48:24.520 --> 48:26.080
 it doesn't screw up with those other ones,

48:26.080 --> 48:29.120
 it doesn't change what those other ones were doing at all.

48:29.120 --> 48:31.320
 So that's really useful for communication

48:31.320 --> 48:33.360
 because that means you can sort of

48:33.360 --> 48:35.640
 allow a lot of these photons to flow

48:36.840 --> 48:38.880
 without disruption of each other

48:38.880 --> 48:41.160
 and they can branch really easily and things like that,

48:41.160 --> 48:42.760
 but it's not good for computation

48:42.760 --> 48:46.400
 because it's very hard for this packet of light

48:46.400 --> 48:48.760
 to change what this packet of light is doing.

48:48.760 --> 48:50.240
 They pass right through each other.

48:50.240 --> 48:53.320
 So in computation, you want to change information

48:53.320 --> 48:55.760
 and if photons don't interact with each other,

48:55.760 --> 48:57.400
 it's difficult to get them to change

48:57.400 --> 48:59.440
 the information represented by the others.

48:59.440 --> 49:01.440
 So that's the fundamental difference.

49:01.440 --> 49:04.800
 Is there also something about the way they travel

49:04.800 --> 49:06.440
 through different materials

49:07.520 --> 49:10.720
 or is that just a particular engineering?

49:10.720 --> 49:12.600
 No, it's not, that's deep physics, I think.

49:12.600 --> 49:17.080
 So this gets back to electrons interact with each other

49:17.080 --> 49:18.160
 and photons don't.

49:18.160 --> 49:22.440
 So say I'm trying to get a packet of information

49:22.440 --> 49:25.840
 from me to you and we have a wire going between us.

49:25.840 --> 49:29.040
 In order for me to send electrons across that wire,

49:29.040 --> 49:32.200
 I first have to raise the voltage at my end of the wire

49:32.200 --> 49:34.600
 and that means putting a bunch of charges on it

49:34.600 --> 49:39.160
 and then that charge packet has to propagate along the wire

49:39.160 --> 49:40.640
 and it has to get all the way over to you.

49:40.640 --> 49:42.720
 There's, that wire is gonna have something

49:42.720 --> 49:45.800
 that's called capacitance which basically tells you

49:45.800 --> 49:48.080
 how much charge you need to put on the wire

49:48.080 --> 49:49.960
 in order to raise the voltage on it

49:49.960 --> 49:52.520
 and the capacitance is gonna be proportional

49:52.520 --> 49:54.040
 to the length of the wire.

49:54.040 --> 49:56.880
 So the longer the length of the wire is,

49:56.880 --> 49:59.120
 the more charge I have to put on it

49:59.120 --> 50:03.080
 and the energy required to charge up that line

50:03.080 --> 50:04.960
 and move those electrons to you

50:04.960 --> 50:06.840
 is also proportional to the capacitance

50:06.840 --> 50:08.480
 and goes as the voltage squared.

50:08.480 --> 50:10.560
 So you get this huge penalty

50:10.560 --> 50:15.040
 if you wanna send electrons across a wire

50:15.040 --> 50:16.600
 over appreciable distances.

50:16.600 --> 50:19.120
 So distance is an important thing here

50:19.120 --> 50:20.800
 when you're doing communication.

50:20.800 --> 50:22.120
 Distance is an important thing.

50:22.120 --> 50:25.360
 So is the number of connections I'm trying to make.

50:25.360 --> 50:27.640
 Me to you, okay, one, that's not so bad.

50:27.640 --> 50:31.440
 If I want to now send it to 10,000 other friends

50:31.440 --> 50:34.360
 then all of those wires are adding tons

50:34.360 --> 50:35.480
 of extra capacitance.

50:35.480 --> 50:37.680
 Now, not only does it take forever

50:37.680 --> 50:39.560
 to put the charge on that wire

50:39.560 --> 50:41.840
 and raise the voltage on all those lines

50:41.840 --> 50:43.560
 but it takes a ton of power

50:43.560 --> 50:47.000
 and the number 10,000 is not randomly chosen.

50:47.000 --> 50:49.120
 That's roughly how many connections

50:49.120 --> 50:50.640
 each neuron in your brain makes.

50:50.640 --> 50:55.080
 So a neuron in your brain needs to send 10,000 messages

50:55.080 --> 50:56.800
 every time it has something to say.

50:56.800 --> 51:00.160
 You can't do that if you're trying to drive electrons

51:00.160 --> 51:02.120
 from here to 10,000 different places.

51:02.120 --> 51:03.720
 The brain does it in a slightly different way

51:03.720 --> 51:04.920
 which we can discuss.

51:04.920 --> 51:07.080
 How can light achieve the 10,000 connections

51:07.080 --> 51:12.000
 and why is it better in terms of like the energy use

51:12.000 --> 51:14.240
 required to use light for the communication

51:14.240 --> 51:15.360
 of the 10,000 connections?

51:15.360 --> 51:16.200
 Right, right.

51:16.200 --> 51:17.720
 So now instead of trying to send electrons

51:17.720 --> 51:19.400
 for me to you, I'm trying to send photons.

51:19.400 --> 51:21.560
 So I can make what's called a wave guide

51:21.560 --> 51:25.160
 which is just a simple piece of a material.

51:25.160 --> 51:27.120
 It could be glass like an optical fiber

51:27.120 --> 51:29.920
 or silicon on a chip.

51:29.920 --> 51:34.200
 And I just have to inject photons into that wave guide

51:34.200 --> 51:35.840
 and independent of how long it is,

51:35.840 --> 51:39.680
 independent of how many different connections I'm making,

51:39.680 --> 51:43.160
 it doesn't change the voltage or anything like that

51:43.160 --> 51:45.520
 that I have to raise up on the wire.

51:45.520 --> 51:47.960
 So if I have one more connection,

51:47.960 --> 51:49.840
 if I add additional connections,

51:49.840 --> 51:51.800
 I need to add more light to the wave guide

51:51.800 --> 51:53.320
 because those photons need to split

51:53.320 --> 51:55.080
 and go to different paths.

51:55.080 --> 51:55.920
 That makes sense.

51:55.920 --> 51:58.880
 But I don't have a capacitive penalty.

51:58.880 --> 52:01.320
 Sometimes these are called wiring parasitics.

52:01.320 --> 52:03.480
 There are no parasitics associated with light

52:03.480 --> 52:04.480
 in that same sense.

52:04.480 --> 52:05.320
 So.

52:05.320 --> 52:07.520
 Well, just to, this might be a dumb question,

52:07.520 --> 52:10.960
 but how do I catch a photon on the other end?

52:10.960 --> 52:12.520
 What's, is it material?

52:12.520 --> 52:15.040
 Is it the polymer stuff you were talking about

52:15.040 --> 52:19.400
 for the, for a different application for photolithography?

52:19.400 --> 52:21.000
 Like how do you catch a photon?

52:21.000 --> 52:22.520
 There's a lot of ways to catch a photon.

52:22.520 --> 52:23.640
 It's not a dumb question.

52:23.640 --> 52:25.960
 It's a, it's a deep and important question

52:25.960 --> 52:29.240
 that basically defines a lot of the work

52:29.240 --> 52:31.400
 that goes on in our group at NIST.

52:31.400 --> 52:33.440
 One of my group leaders,

52:33.440 --> 52:35.360
 Sey Woonam has built his career

52:35.360 --> 52:38.440
 around these superconducting single photon detectors.

52:38.440 --> 52:42.480
 So if you're going to try to sort of reach a lower limit

52:42.480 --> 52:45.280
 and detect just one particle of light,

52:45.280 --> 52:47.680
 superconductors come back into our conversation

52:47.680 --> 52:50.160
 and just picture a simple device

52:50.160 --> 52:51.880
 where you have current flowing through

52:51.880 --> 52:54.640
 a superconducting wire and.

52:54.640 --> 52:56.600
 A loop again or no?

52:56.600 --> 52:57.840
 Let's say yes, you have a loop.

52:57.840 --> 52:59.600
 So you have a superconducting wire

52:59.600 --> 53:01.040
 that goes straight down like this

53:01.040 --> 53:02.600
 and on, on your loop branch,

53:02.600 --> 53:04.280
 you have a little ammeter,

53:04.280 --> 53:05.840
 something that measures current.

53:05.840 --> 53:09.040
 There's a resistor up there to go with me here.

53:09.040 --> 53:12.040
 So you're, you're current biasing this.

53:12.040 --> 53:13.240
 So there's current flowing through

53:13.240 --> 53:14.440
 that superconducting branch.

53:14.440 --> 53:16.600
 Since there's a resistor over here,

53:16.600 --> 53:18.960
 all the current goes through the superconducting branch.

53:18.960 --> 53:22.320
 Now a photon comes in, strikes that superconductor.

53:22.320 --> 53:24.320
 We talked about this superconducting

53:24.320 --> 53:25.800
 macroscopic quantum state.

53:25.800 --> 53:28.520
 That's going to be destroyed by the energy of that photon.

53:28.520 --> 53:32.120
 So now that branch of the circuit is resistive too.

53:32.120 --> 53:33.800
 And you've properly designed your circuit

53:33.800 --> 53:36.720
 so that the resistance on that superconducting branch

53:36.720 --> 53:38.440
 is much greater than the other resistance.

53:38.440 --> 53:40.800
 Now all of your current is going to go that way.

53:40.800 --> 53:43.280
 Your ammeter says, oh, I just got a pulse of current.

53:43.280 --> 53:45.160
 That must mean I detected a photon.

53:45.160 --> 53:47.240
 Then where you broke that superconductivity

53:47.240 --> 53:49.120
 in a matter of a few nanoseconds,

53:49.120 --> 53:51.120
 it cools back off, dissipates that energy

53:51.120 --> 53:52.960
 and the current flows back through

53:52.960 --> 53:54.280
 that superconducting branch.

53:54.280 --> 53:59.280
 This is a very powerful superconducting device

53:59.280 --> 54:02.280
 that allows us to understand quantum states of light.

54:02.280 --> 54:04.880
 I didn't realize a loop like that

54:04.880 --> 54:07.160
 could be sensitive to a single photon.

54:07.160 --> 54:11.360
 I mean, that seems strange to me.

54:11.360 --> 54:14.360
 Because, I mean, so what happens

54:14.360 --> 54:16.600
 when you just barrage it with photons?

54:16.600 --> 54:18.360
 If you put a bunch of photons in there,

54:18.360 --> 54:19.880
 essentially the same thing happens.

54:19.880 --> 54:21.680
 You just drive it into the normal state,

54:21.680 --> 54:23.160
 it becomes resistive,

54:23.160 --> 54:25.400
 and it's not particularly interesting.

54:25.400 --> 54:28.000
 So you have to be careful how many photons you send.

54:28.000 --> 54:30.080
 Like you have to be very precise with your communication.

54:30.080 --> 54:31.200
 Well, it depends.

54:31.200 --> 54:34.200
 So I would say that that's actually in the application

54:34.200 --> 54:37.040
 that we're trying to use these detectors for.

54:37.040 --> 54:39.840
 That's a feature because what we want is for,

54:41.120 --> 54:46.120
 if a neuron sends one photon to a synaptic connection

54:46.640 --> 54:49.840
 and one of these superconducting detectors is sitting there,

54:49.840 --> 54:51.200
 you get this pulse of current

54:51.200 --> 54:54.000
 and that synapse says event,

54:54.000 --> 54:56.040
 then I'm gonna do what I do when there's a synapse event,

54:56.040 --> 54:58.640
 I'm gonna perform computations, that kind of thing.

54:58.640 --> 55:02.080
 But if accidentally you send two there or three or five,

55:02.080 --> 55:03.360
 it does the exact same.

55:03.360 --> 55:04.200
 Got it.

55:04.200 --> 55:09.200
 So this is how in the system that we're devising here,

55:10.080 --> 55:12.800
 communication is entirely binary.

55:12.800 --> 55:15.080
 And that's what I tried to emphasize a second ago.

55:15.080 --> 55:17.840
 Communication should not change the information.

55:17.840 --> 55:19.440
 You're not saying,

55:19.440 --> 55:22.320
 oh, I got this kind of communication event for photons.

55:22.320 --> 55:23.760
 No, we're not keeping track of that.

55:23.760 --> 55:26.640
 This neuron fired, this synapse says that neuron fired.

55:26.640 --> 55:27.480
 That's it.

55:27.480 --> 55:31.520
 So that's a noise filtering property of those detectors.

55:31.520 --> 55:33.200
 However, there are other applications

55:33.200 --> 55:36.200
 where you'd rather know the exact number of photons.

55:36.200 --> 55:39.360
 That can be very useful in quantum computing with light.

55:39.360 --> 55:42.200
 And our group does a lot of work around

55:42.200 --> 55:44.640
 another kind of superconducting sensor

55:44.640 --> 55:46.720
 called a transition edge sensor

55:46.720 --> 55:50.000
 that Adrian Alida in our group does a lot of work on that.

55:50.000 --> 55:52.640
 And that can tell you,

55:52.640 --> 55:55.840
 based on the amplitude of the current pulse you divert,

55:55.840 --> 56:00.320
 exactly how many photons were in that pulse.

56:00.320 --> 56:01.160
 So...

56:01.160 --> 56:02.480
 What's that useful for?

56:02.480 --> 56:04.680
 One way that you can encode information

56:04.680 --> 56:07.400
 in quantum states of light is in the number of photons.

56:07.400 --> 56:09.280
 You can have what are called number states.

56:09.280 --> 56:13.000
 And a number state will have a well defined number of photons.

56:13.000 --> 56:16.360
 And maybe the output of your quantum computation

56:16.360 --> 56:19.720
 encodes its information in the number of photons

56:19.720 --> 56:20.560
 that are generated.

56:20.560 --> 56:23.000
 So if you have a detector that is sensitive to that,

56:23.000 --> 56:24.240
 it's extremely useful.

56:24.240 --> 56:29.240
 Can you achieve like a clock with photons?

