 And I think that's an important part of why it can do what it does.

1:00:46.280 --> 1:00:48.680
 But okay, let me try to break it down.

1:00:49.600 --> 1:00:54.600
 Starting with the devices, neurons, as I said before,

1:00:54.960 --> 1:00:57.080
 they're sophisticated devices in and of themselves

1:00:57.080 --> 1:00:58.200
 and synapses are too.

1:00:58.200 --> 1:01:03.040
 They can change their state based on the activity

1:01:03.040 --> 1:01:04.880
 so they adapt over time.

1:01:04.880 --> 1:01:06.960
 That's crucial to the way the brain works.

1:01:06.960 --> 1:01:09.360
 They don't just adapt on one time scale,

1:01:09.360 --> 1:01:12.440
 they can adapt on myriad time scales

1:01:12.440 --> 1:01:16.040
 from the spacing between pulses,

1:01:16.040 --> 1:01:18.680
 the spacing between spikes that come from neurons

1:01:18.680 --> 1:01:21.520
 all the way to the age of the organism.

1:01:23.080 --> 1:01:26.240
 Also relevant, perhaps,

1:01:26.240 --> 1:01:29.200
 I think the most important thing that's guided my thinking

1:01:29.200 --> 1:01:33.000
 is the network structure of the brain.

1:01:33.000 --> 1:01:33.840
 So...

1:01:33.840 --> 1:01:36.320
 Which can also be adjusted on different scales.

1:01:36.320 --> 1:01:37.160
 Yeah, absolutely.

1:01:37.160 --> 1:01:41.320
 Yeah, so you're changing the strength of contacts,

1:01:41.320 --> 1:01:44.080
 you're changing the spatial distribution of them.

1:01:44.080 --> 1:01:46.880
 Although spatial distribution doesn't change that much

1:01:46.880 --> 1:01:49.400
 once you're a mature organism,

1:01:49.400 --> 1:01:52.880
 but that network structure is really crucial.

1:01:52.880 --> 1:01:55.400
 So let me dwell on that for a second.

1:01:57.160 --> 1:01:59.360
 You can't talk about the brain without emphasizing that

1:01:59.360 --> 1:02:02.840
 most of the neurons in the neocortex

1:02:02.840 --> 1:02:04.080
 or the prefrontal cortex,

1:02:04.080 --> 1:02:06.280
 the part of the brain that we think is most responsible

1:02:06.280 --> 1:02:09.080
 for high level reasoning and things like that,

1:02:09.080 --> 1:02:11.360
 those neurons make thousands of connections.

1:02:11.360 --> 1:02:15.600
 So you have this network that is highly interconnected.

1:02:15.600 --> 1:02:19.920
 And I think it's safe to say that one of the primary reasons

1:02:19.920 --> 1:02:23.200
 that they make so many different connections

1:02:23.200 --> 1:02:26.920
 is that allows information to be communicated very rapidly

1:02:26.920 --> 1:02:28.440
 from any spot in the network

1:02:28.440 --> 1:02:30.360
 to any other spot in the network.

1:02:30.360 --> 1:02:33.960
 So that's a sort of spatial aspect of it.

1:02:33.960 --> 1:02:38.520
 You can quantify this in terms of concepts

1:02:38.520 --> 1:02:41.040
 that are related to fractals and scale invariance,

1:02:41.040 --> 1:02:43.280
 which I think is a very beautiful concept.

1:02:43.280 --> 1:02:46.240
 So what I mean by that is kind of,

1:02:46.240 --> 1:02:50.760
 no matter what spatial scale you're looking at in the brain,

1:02:50.760 --> 1:02:52.360
 within certain bounds,

1:02:52.360 --> 1:02:55.000
 you see the same general statistical pattern.

1:02:55.000 --> 1:02:58.640
 So if I draw a box around some region of my cortex,

1:02:59.600 --> 1:03:02.320
 most of the connections that those neurons

1:03:02.320 --> 1:03:04.520
 within that box make are gonna be within the box

1:03:04.520 --> 1:03:06.240
 to each other in their local neighborhood.

1:03:06.240 --> 1:03:09.320
 And that's sort of called clustering, loosely speaking.

1:03:09.320 --> 1:03:12.640
 But a non negligible fraction is gonna go outside of that box.

1:03:12.640 --> 1:03:14.120
 And then if I draw a bigger box,

1:03:14.120 --> 1:03:16.440
 the pattern is gonna be exactly the same.

1:03:16.440 --> 1:03:18.440
 So you have this scale invariance,

1:03:18.440 --> 1:03:22.720
 and you also have a non vanishing probability

1:03:22.720 --> 1:03:25.400
 of a neuron making connection very far away.

1:03:25.400 --> 1:03:28.720
 So suppose you wanna plot the probability

1:03:28.720 --> 1:03:32.440
 of a neuron making a connection as a function of distance.

1:03:32.440 --> 1:03:34.240
 If that weren't exponential function,

1:03:34.240 --> 1:03:36.720
 it would go E to the minus radius

1:03:36.720 --> 1:03:38.720
 over some characteristic radius,

1:03:38.720 --> 1:03:41.840
 and it would drop off up to some certain radius.

1:03:41.840 --> 1:03:44.920
 The probability would be reasonable close to one.

1:03:44.920 --> 1:03:49.120
 And then beyond that characteristic length R zero,

1:03:49.120 --> 1:03:51.320
 it would drop off sharply.

1:03:51.320 --> 1:03:53.560
 And so that would mean that the neurons in your brain

1:03:53.560 --> 1:03:56.320
 are really localized.

1:03:56.320 --> 1:03:58.640
 And that's not what we observe.

1:03:58.640 --> 1:04:00.680
 And instead, what you see is that the probability

1:04:00.680 --> 1:04:02.720
 of making a longer distance connection,

1:04:02.720 --> 1:04:05.840
 it does drop off, but it drops off as a power loss.

1:04:05.840 --> 1:04:08.440
 So the probability that you're gonna have a connection

1:04:08.440 --> 1:04:13.200
 at some radius R goes as R to the minus some power.

1:04:13.200 --> 1:04:16.800
 And that's what we see with forces in nature,

1:04:16.800 --> 1:04:19.400
 like the electromagnetic force between two particles

1:04:19.400 --> 1:04:23.000
 or gravity goes as one over the radius squared.

1:04:23.000 --> 1:04:23.840
 So...

1:04:23.840 --> 1:04:24.680
 You can see this in fractals.

1:04:24.680 --> 1:04:28.600
 I love that there's like a fractal dynamics of the brain.

1:04:28.600 --> 1:04:31.440
 That if you zoom out, you draw the box

1:04:31.440 --> 1:04:35.040
 and you increase that box by certain step sizes,

1:04:35.040 --> 1:04:36.720
 you're gonna see the same statistics.

1:04:36.720 --> 1:04:40.000
 I think that's probably very important

1:04:40.000 --> 1:04:41.880
 to the way the brain processes information.

1:04:41.880 --> 1:04:43.600
 It's not just in the spatial domain,

1:04:43.600 --> 1:04:45.640
 it's also in the temporal domain.

1:04:45.640 --> 1:04:47.200
 And what I mean by that is...

1:04:48.640 --> 1:04:50.600
 That's incredible that this emerged

1:04:50.600 --> 1:04:52.320
 through the evolutionary process

1:04:52.320 --> 1:04:54.880
 that potentially somehow connected

1:04:54.880 --> 1:04:57.800
 to the way the physics of the universe works.

1:04:57.800 --> 1:04:59.360
 Yeah, I couldn't agree more.

1:04:59.360 --> 1:05:01.440
 That it's a deep and fascinating subject

1:05:01.440 --> 1:05:04.160
 that I hope to be able to spend the rest of my life studying.

1:05:04.160 --> 1:05:07.320
 Do you think you need to solve, understand this,

1:05:07.320 --> 1:05:09.520
 this fractal nature in order to understand

1:05:09.520 --> 1:05:10.760
 intelligence and communication?

1:05:10.760 --> 1:05:11.600
 I do think so.

1:05:11.600 --> 1:05:13.360
 I think they're deeply intertwined.

1:05:13.360 --> 1:05:16.920
 Yes, I think power laws are right at the heart of it.

1:05:16.920 --> 1:05:19.360
 So just to push that one through,

1:05:19.360 --> 1:05:21.520
 the same thing happens in the temporal domain.

1:05:21.520 --> 1:05:23.200
 So suppose you had...

1:05:24.400 --> 1:05:26.040
 Suppose your neurons in your brain

1:05:26.040 --> 1:05:28.200
 were always oscillating at the same frequency.

1:05:28.200 --> 1:05:30.760
 Then the probability of finding a neuron

1:05:30.760 --> 1:05:32.560
 oscillating as a function of frequency

1:05:32.560 --> 1:05:34.560
 would be this narrowly peaked function

1:05:34.560 --> 1:05:36.560
 around that certain characteristic frequency.

1:05:36.560 --> 1:05:37.920
 That's not at all what we see.

1:05:37.920 --> 1:05:40.280
 The probability of finding neurons oscillating

1:05:40.280 --> 1:05:43.920
 or pulsing, producing spikes at a certain frequency

1:05:43.920 --> 1:05:45.240
 is again a power law,

1:05:45.240 --> 1:05:49.680
 which means there's no defined scale

1:05:49.680 --> 1:05:51.720
 of the temporal activity in the brain.

1:05:53.720 --> 1:05:56.080
 At what speed do your thoughts occur?

1:05:56.080 --> 1:05:58.320
 Well, there's a fastest speed they can occur,

1:05:58.320 --> 1:06:01.520
 and that is limited by communication and other things,

1:06:01.520 --> 1:06:03.960
 but there's not a characteristic scale.

1:06:03.960 --> 1:06:06.920
 We have thoughts on all temporal scales

1:06:06.920 --> 1:06:10.840
 from a few tens of milliseconds,

1:06:10.840 --> 1:06:13.400
 which is physiologically limited by our devices,

1:06:13.400 --> 1:06:15.760
 compare that to tens of picoseconds

1:06:15.760 --> 1:06:17.160
 that I talked about in superconductors,

1:06:17.160 --> 1:06:19.280
 all the way up to the lifetime of the organism.

1:06:19.280 --> 1:06:20.760
 You can still think about things

1:06:20.760 --> 1:06:22.600
 that happened to you when you were a kid.

1:06:22.600 --> 1:06:24.120
 Well, if you want to be really trippy

1:06:24.120 --> 1:06:25.880
 then across multiple organisms

1:06:25.880 --> 1:06:27.480
 in the entirety of human civilization,

1:06:27.480 --> 1:06:29.440
 you have thoughts that span organisms, right?

1:06:29.440 --> 1:06:31.240
 Yes, taking it to that level.

1:06:31.240 --> 1:06:34.680
 If you're willing to see the entirety of the human species

1:06:34.680 --> 1:06:37.240
 as a single organism with a collective intelligence,

1:06:37.240 --> 1:06:39.960
 then that too on a spatial and temporal scale,

1:06:39.960 --> 1:06:41.160
 there's thoughts occurring.

1:06:41.160 --> 1:06:44.080
 And then if you look at not just the human species,

1:06:44.080 --> 1:06:46.560
 but the entirety of life on earth

1:06:46.560 --> 1:06:49.680
 as an organism with thoughts that are occurring

1:06:49.680 --> 1:06:51.680
 that are greater and greater sophisticated thoughts,

1:06:51.680 --> 1:06:54.720
 there's a different spatial and temporal scale there.

1:06:54.720 --> 1:06:57.280
 This is getting very suspicious.

1:06:57.280 --> 1:06:58.120
 Well, hold on though.

1:06:58.120 --> 1:07:01.040
 Before we're done, I just want to just tie the bow

1:07:01.040 --> 1:07:04.360
 and say that the spatial and temporal aspects

1:07:04.360 --> 1:07:06.520
 are intimately interrelated with each other.

1:07:06.520 --> 1:07:09.880
 So activity between neurons that are very close

1:07:09.880 --> 1:07:11.560
 to each other is more likely to happen

1:07:11.560 --> 1:07:13.640
 on this faster time scale.

1:07:13.640 --> 1:07:15.360
 And information is going to propagate

1:07:15.360 --> 1:07:17.280
 and encompass more of the brain,

1:07:17.280 --> 1:07:20.320
 more of your cortices, different modules in the brain

1:07:20.320 --> 1:07:23.800
 are going to be engaged in information processing

1:07:23.800 --> 1:07:25.320
 on longer time scale.

1:07:25.320 --> 1:07:28.000
 So there's this concept of information integration

1:07:28.000 --> 1:07:32.000
 where most neurons are specialized.

1:07:32.000 --> 1:07:34.040
 Any given neuron or any cluster of neuron

1:07:34.040 --> 1:07:35.800
 has its specific purpose,

1:07:35.800 --> 1:07:39.960
 but they're also very much integrated.

1:07:39.960 --> 1:07:41.960
 So you have neurons that specialize,

1:07:41.960 --> 1:07:43.720
 but share their information.

1:07:43.720 --> 1:07:47.640
 And so that happens through these fractal nested oscillations

1:07:47.640 --> 1:07:49.480
 that occur across spatial and temporal scales.

1:07:49.480 --> 1:07:53.720
 I think capturing those dynamics in hardware,

1:07:53.720 --> 1:07:57.120
 to me, that's the goal of neuromorphic computing.

1:07:57.120 --> 1:07:58.720
 So does it need to look...

1:07:58.720 --> 1:08:00.880
 So first of all, that's fascinating.

1:08:00.880 --> 1:08:04.000
 We stated some clear principles here.

1:08:04.000 --> 1:08:08.160
 Now, does it have to look like the brain

1:08:08.160 --> 1:08:09.840
 outside of those principles as well?

1:08:09.840 --> 1:08:11.360
 Like what other characteristics

1:08:11.360 --> 1:08:13.120
 have to look like the human brain?

1:08:13.120 --> 1:08:15.880
 Or can it be something very different?

1:08:15.880 --> 1:08:18.040
 Well, it depends on what you're trying to use it for.

1:08:18.040 --> 1:08:20.760
 And so I think a lot of the community

1:08:21.760 --> 1:08:23.120
 asks that question a lot.

1:08:23.120 --> 1:08:24.400
 What are you going to do with it?

1:08:24.400 --> 1:08:26.640
 And I completely get it.

1:08:26.640 --> 1:08:28.040
 I think that's a very important question.

1:08:28.040 --> 1:08:31.880
 And it's also sometimes not the most helpful question.

1:08:31.880 --> 1:08:33.800
 What if what you want to do with it is study it?

1:08:33.800 --> 1:08:35.200
 What if you just want to see...

1:08:36.760 --> 1:08:39.280
 What do you have to build into your hardware

1:08:39.280 --> 1:08:42.240
 in order to observe these dynamical principles?

1:08:42.240 --> 1:08:43.240
 So...

1:08:43.240 --> 1:08:45.640
 And also, I ask sometimes...

1:08:45.640 --> 1:08:47.560
 I ask myself that question every day,

1:08:47.560 --> 1:08:49.880
 and I'm not sure I'm able to answer that.

1:08:49.880 --> 1:08:51.240
 It's like, what are you going to do

1:08:51.240 --> 1:08:53.520
 with this particular neuromorphic machine?

1:08:53.520 --> 1:08:55.360
 So suppose what we're trying to do with it

1:08:55.360 --> 1:08:57.000
 is build something that thinks.

1:08:57.000 --> 1:08:59.160
 We're not trying to get it to make us any money

1:08:59.160 --> 1:09:00.240
 or drive a car.

1:09:00.240 --> 1:09:01.680
 Maybe we'll be able to do that.

1:09:01.680 --> 1:09:02.640
 But that's not our goal.

1:09:02.640 --> 1:09:06.280
 Our goal is to see if we can get the same types

1:09:06.280 --> 1:09:08.920
 of behaviors that we observe in our own brain.

1:09:08.920 --> 1:09:10.480
 And by behaviors, in this sense,

1:09:10.480 --> 1:09:14.320
 what I mean the behaviors of the components,

1:09:14.320 --> 1:09:16.000
 the neurons, the network, that kind of stuff.

1:09:16.000 --> 1:09:17.440
 I think there's another element

1:09:17.440 --> 1:09:19.120
 that I didn't really hit on

1:09:19.120 --> 1:09:21.200
 that you also have to build into this.

1:09:21.200 --> 1:09:22.920
 And those are architectural principles.

1:09:22.920 --> 1:09:26.640
 They have to do with the hierarchical modular construction

1:09:26.640 --> 1:09:27.480
 of the network.

1:09:27.480 --> 1:09:30.200
 And without getting too lost and jargon,

1:09:30.200 --> 1:09:33.680
 the main point that I think is relevant there,

1:09:33.680 --> 1:09:35.720
 let me try and illustrate it with a cartoon picture

1:09:35.720 --> 1:09:38.200
 of the architecture of the brain.

1:09:38.200 --> 1:09:41.120
 So in the brain, you have the cortex,

1:09:41.120 --> 1:09:43.560
 which is sort of this outer sheet.

1:09:45.720 --> 1:09:47.160
 It's a layered structure.

1:09:47.160 --> 1:09:48.480
 If you could take it out of your brain,

1:09:48.480 --> 1:09:50.680
 you could unroll it on the table,

1:09:50.680 --> 1:09:52.840
 and it would be about the size of a pizza.

1:09:52.840 --> 1:09:53.680
 Sitting there.

1:09:54.560 --> 1:09:57.320
 And that's a module.

1:09:57.320 --> 1:09:58.720
 It does certain things.

1:09:58.720 --> 1:10:01.720
 It processes as Yorgi Buzaki would say,

1:10:01.720 --> 1:10:04.480
 it processes the what of what's going on around you.

1:10:04.480 --> 1:10:07.200
 But you have another really crucial module

1:10:07.200 --> 1:10:09.000
 that's called the hippocampus.

1:10:09.000 --> 1:10:11.480
 And that network is structured entirely differently.

1:10:11.480 --> 1:10:12.920
 First of all, this cortex

1:10:12.920 --> 1:10:15.600
 that I described, 10 billion neurons in there.

1:10:15.600 --> 1:10:17.840
 So numbers matter here.

1:10:17.840 --> 1:10:21.400
 And they're organized in that sort of power law distribution

1:10:21.400 --> 1:10:23.240
 where the probability of making a connection

1:10:23.240 --> 1:10:25.320
 drops off as a power law in space.

1:10:25.320 --> 1:10:27.000
 The hippocampus is another module

1:10:27.000 --> 1:10:30.280
 that's important for understanding how,

1:10:30.280 --> 1:10:33.040
 where you are, when you are,

1:10:34.160 --> 1:10:38.000
 keeping track of your position in space and time.

1:10:38.000 --> 1:10:40.040
 And that network is very much random.

1:10:40.040 --> 1:10:42.800
 So the probability of making a connection,

1:10:42.800 --> 1:10:45.560
 it almost doesn't even drop off as a function of distance.

1:10:45.560 --> 1:10:46.680
 It's the same probability

1:10:46.680 --> 1:10:48.480
 that you'll make it here to over there.

1:10:48.480 --> 1:10:51.480
 But there are only about a hundred million neurons there.

1:10:51.480 --> 1:10:55.160
 So you can have that huge, densely connected module

1:10:55.160 --> 1:10:57.760
 because it's not so big.

1:10:57.760 --> 1:11:02.520
 And the neocortex or the cortex and the hippocampus,

1:11:02.520 --> 1:11:05.400
 they talk to each other constantly.

1:11:05.400 --> 1:11:08.400
 And that communication is largely facilitated

1:11:08.400 --> 1:11:10.200
 by what's called the thalamus.

1:11:10.200 --> 1:11:11.360
 I'm not a neuroscientist here.

