1:15:16.600 --> 1:15:19.560
 of neuroscience and neuromorphic computing as well.

1:15:19.560 --> 1:15:24.560
 So there are two poles to that on that spectrum one.

1:15:26.720 --> 1:15:28.880
 Okay, so in more in the language of machine learning,

1:15:28.880 --> 1:15:32.000
 we would talk about supervised and unsupervised learning

1:15:32.000 --> 1:15:35.520
 in when I'm trying to tie that down to neuromorphic computing,

1:15:35.520 --> 1:15:38.440
 I will use a definition of supervised learning,

1:15:38.440 --> 1:15:43.000
 which basically means the external user,

1:15:43.000 --> 1:15:45.520
 the person who's controlling this hardware

1:15:45.520 --> 1:15:48.360
 has some knob that they can tune

1:15:48.360 --> 1:15:50.440
 to change each of the synaptic weights

1:15:50.440 --> 1:15:52.440
 depending on whether or not the network's doing

1:15:52.440 --> 1:15:53.560
 what you want it to do.

1:15:53.560 --> 1:15:56.160
 Whereas what I mean in this conversation

1:15:56.160 --> 1:15:58.360
 when I say unsupervised learning is that

1:15:58.360 --> 1:16:02.320
 those synaptic weights are dynamically changing

1:16:02.320 --> 1:16:05.000
 in your network based on nothing that the user is doing,

1:16:05.000 --> 1:16:07.080
 nothing that there's no wire from the outside

1:16:07.080 --> 1:16:09.040
 going into any of those synapses.

1:16:09.040 --> 1:16:12.080
 The network itself is reconfiguring those synaptic weights

1:16:12.080 --> 1:16:15.760
 based on physical properties

1:16:15.760 --> 1:16:17.600
 that you've built into the devices.

1:16:17.600 --> 1:16:21.400
 So if the synapse receives a pulse from here

1:16:21.400 --> 1:16:23.360
 and that causes the neuron to spike,

1:16:23.360 --> 1:16:27.040
 some circuit built in there with no help from me

1:16:27.040 --> 1:16:29.800
 or anybody else adjust the weight in a way

1:16:29.800 --> 1:16:34.600
 that makes it more likely to store the useful information

1:16:34.600 --> 1:16:36.400
 and excite the useful network patterns

1:16:36.400 --> 1:16:39.360
 and makes it less likely that random noise,

1:16:39.360 --> 1:16:41.920
 useless communication events will have

1:16:41.920 --> 1:16:45.320
 an important effect on the network activity.

1:16:45.320 --> 1:16:48.280
 So there's memory encoded in the weights,

1:16:48.280 --> 1:16:49.760
 the synaptic weights.

1:16:49.760 --> 1:16:51.880
 What about the formation of something

1:16:51.880 --> 1:16:53.680
 that's not often done in machine learning,

1:16:53.680 --> 1:16:56.280
 the formation of new synaptic connections?

1:16:56.280 --> 1:16:57.440
 Right, well that seems to,

1:16:57.440 --> 1:17:00.120
 so again, not a neuroscientist here,

1:17:00.120 --> 1:17:02.160
 but my reading of the literature is that

1:17:02.160 --> 1:17:05.000
 that's particularly crucial in early stages

1:17:05.000 --> 1:17:09.120
 of brain development where a newborn is born

1:17:09.120 --> 1:17:11.680
 with tons of extra synaptic connections

1:17:11.680 --> 1:17:13.880
 and it's actually pruned over time.

1:17:13.880 --> 1:17:16.800
 So the number of synapses decreases

1:17:16.800 --> 1:17:19.680
 as opposed to growing new long distance connections.

1:17:19.680 --> 1:17:22.280
 It is possible in the brain to grow new neurons

1:17:22.280 --> 1:17:26.080
 and assign new synaptic connections,

1:17:26.080 --> 1:17:29.120
 but it doesn't seem to be the primary mechanism

1:17:29.120 --> 1:17:31.840
 by which the brain is learning.

1:17:31.840 --> 1:17:35.720
 So for example, like right now, sitting here talking to you,

1:17:35.720 --> 1:17:37.000
 you say lots of interesting things

1:17:37.000 --> 1:17:40.520
 and I learn from you and I can remember things

1:17:40.520 --> 1:17:41.360
 that you just said,

1:17:41.360 --> 1:17:44.720
 and I didn't grow new axonal connections

1:17:44.720 --> 1:17:47.360
 down to new synapses to enable those.

1:17:47.360 --> 1:17:52.160
 It's plasticity mechanisms in the synaptic connections

1:17:52.160 --> 1:17:55.960
 between neurons that enable me to learn on that time scale.

1:17:55.960 --> 1:17:59.400
 So at the very least that you can sufficiently approximate

1:17:59.400 --> 1:18:01.360
 that with just weight updates,

1:18:01.360 --> 1:18:03.000
 you don't need to form new connections.

1:18:03.000 --> 1:18:05.080
 I would say weight updates are a big part of it.

1:18:05.080 --> 1:18:08.640
 I also think there's more because broadly speaking,

1:18:08.640 --> 1:18:10.440
 when we're doing machine learning,

1:18:10.440 --> 1:18:12.480
 our networks say we're talking about feed forward,

1:18:12.480 --> 1:18:15.800
 deep neural networks, the temporal domain

1:18:15.800 --> 1:18:16.920
 is not really part of it.

1:18:16.920 --> 1:18:18.200
 Okay, you're gonna put in an image

1:18:18.200 --> 1:18:20.400
 and you're gonna get out a classification

1:18:20.400 --> 1:18:22.000
 and you're gonna do that as fast as possible.

1:18:22.000 --> 1:18:23.200
 So you care about time,

1:18:23.200 --> 1:18:26.640
 but time is not part of the essence of this thing really.

1:18:27.560 --> 1:18:30.040
 Whereas in spiking neural networks,

1:18:30.040 --> 1:18:31.760
 what we see in the brain,

1:18:31.760 --> 1:18:34.600
 time is as crucial a space in their intimately intertwined

1:18:34.600 --> 1:18:36.000
 as I've tried to say.

1:18:36.000 --> 1:18:41.000
