1:26:49.280 --> 1:26:53.120
 If we had a light source on a silicon chip

1:26:53.120 --> 1:26:55.880
 that was as simple as a transistor,

1:26:55.880 --> 1:26:58.200
 there would not be a processor in the world

1:26:58.200 --> 1:26:59.720
 that didn't use light for communication,

1:26:59.720 --> 1:27:01.760
 at least above some distance.

1:27:01.760 --> 1:27:04.040
 How many light sources are needed?

1:27:04.040 --> 1:27:06.800
 Oh, you need a light source at every single point.

1:27:06.800 --> 1:27:08.400
 A light source per neuron?

1:27:08.400 --> 1:27:09.920
 Per neuron, per little,

1:27:09.920 --> 1:27:14.120
 but then if you could have a really small and nice light source,

1:27:14.120 --> 1:27:17.920
 your definition of neuron could be flexible.

1:27:17.920 --> 1:27:19.160
 Could be, yes, yes.

1:27:19.160 --> 1:27:21.720
 Sometimes it's helpful to me to say,

1:27:21.720 --> 1:27:24.560
 in this hardware, a neuron is that entity

1:27:24.560 --> 1:27:26.120
 which has a light source.

1:27:26.120 --> 1:27:28.000
 And I can explain.

1:27:28.000 --> 1:27:29.560
 And then there was light.

1:27:29.560 --> 1:27:32.280
 I mean, I can explain more about that, but...

1:27:32.280 --> 1:27:34.680
 Somehow this rhymes with consciousness

1:27:34.680 --> 1:27:38.240
 because people will often say the light of consciousness.

1:27:38.240 --> 1:27:41.680
 So that consciousness is that which is conscious.

1:27:41.680 --> 1:27:42.520
 I got it.

1:27:43.600 --> 1:27:44.840
 That's not my quote.

1:27:44.840 --> 1:27:47.000
 That's me. That's my quote.

1:27:47.000 --> 1:27:49.480
 See, that quote comes from my background.

1:27:49.480 --> 1:27:54.880
 Yours is in optics, mine in light, mine is in darkness.

1:27:54.880 --> 1:27:56.480
 So go ahead.

1:27:56.480 --> 1:27:59.600
 So the point I was making there is that

1:27:59.600 --> 1:28:02.960
 if it was easy to manufacture light sources

1:28:02.960 --> 1:28:05.760
 along with transistors on a silicon chip,

1:28:05.760 --> 1:28:07.240
 they would be everywhere.

1:28:07.240 --> 1:28:08.880
 And it's not easy.

1:28:08.880 --> 1:28:10.160
 People have been trying for decades

1:28:10.160 --> 1:28:11.960
 and it's actually extremely difficult.

1:28:11.960 --> 1:28:13.720
 I think an important part of our research

1:28:13.720 --> 1:28:17.360
 is dwelling right at that spot there.

1:28:17.360 --> 1:28:18.760
 Is it physics or engineering?

1:28:18.760 --> 1:28:19.600
 It's physics.

1:28:19.600 --> 1:28:22.280
 So, okay, so it's physics, I think.

1:28:22.280 --> 1:28:26.920
 So what I mean by that is as we discussed,

1:28:26.920 --> 1:28:29.400
 silicon is the material of choice for transistors

1:28:29.400 --> 1:28:33.280
 and it's very difficult to imagine

1:28:33.280 --> 1:28:35.200
 that that's gonna change anytime soon.

1:28:35.200 --> 1:28:39.160
 Silicon is notoriously bad at emitting light

1:28:39.160 --> 1:28:43.280
 and that has to do with the immutable properties

1:28:43.280 --> 1:28:46.240
 of silicon itself, the way that the energy bands

1:28:46.240 --> 1:28:47.880
 are structured in silicon.

1:28:47.880 --> 1:28:50.520
 You're never going to make silicon efficient

1:28:50.520 --> 1:28:53.520
 as a light source at room temperature

1:28:53.520 --> 1:28:55.640
 without doing very exotic things

1:28:55.640 --> 1:28:58.320
 that degrade its ability to interface nicely

1:28:58.320 --> 1:28:59.840
 with those transistors in the first place.

1:28:59.840 --> 1:29:02.600
 So that's like one of these things where it's,

1:29:02.600 --> 1:29:05.200
 why is nature dealing us that blow?

1:29:05.200 --> 1:29:07.000
 You give us these beautiful transistors

1:29:07.000 --> 1:29:08.640
 and you give us all the motivation

1:29:08.640 --> 1:29:10.120
 to use light for communication,

1:29:10.120 --> 1:29:11.520
 but then you don't give us a light source.

1:29:11.520 --> 1:29:14.000
 So, well, okay, you do give us a light source,

1:29:14.000 --> 1:29:15.360
 compound semiconductors.

1:29:15.360 --> 1:29:16.920
 Like we talked about back at the beginning,

1:29:16.920 --> 1:29:19.680
 an element from group three and an element from group five

1:29:19.680 --> 1:29:21.840
 from an alloy where every other lattice site

1:29:21.840 --> 1:29:23.680
 switches which element it is.

1:29:23.680 --> 1:29:27.280
 Those have much better properties for generating light.

1:29:27.280 --> 1:29:30.040
 You put electrons in, light comes out.

1:29:30.040 --> 1:29:33.160
 Almost a hundred percent of the electron hold,

1:29:34.000 --> 1:29:35.360
 it can be made efficient.

1:29:35.360 --> 1:29:37.440
 Okay, I'll take your offer, okay.

1:29:37.440 --> 1:29:39.600
 However, I say it's physics, not engineering,

1:29:39.600 --> 1:29:43.160
 because it's very difficult to get those

1:29:43.160 --> 1:29:45.280
 compound semiconductor light sources

1:29:45.280 --> 1:29:47.560
 situated with your silicon.

1:29:47.560 --> 1:29:49.440
 In order to do that ion implantation

1:29:49.440 --> 1:29:50.800
 that I talked about at the beginning,

1:29:50.800 --> 1:29:52.760
 high temperatures are required.

1:29:52.760 --> 1:29:55.720
 So you gotta make all of your transistors first

1:29:55.720 --> 1:29:58.600
 and then put the compound semiconductors on top of there.

1:29:58.600 --> 1:30:00.840
 You can't grow them afterwards

1:30:00.840 --> 1:30:02.400
 because that requires high temperature.

1:30:02.400 --> 1:30:04.040
 It screws up all your transistors.

1:30:04.040 --> 1:30:05.840
 You try and stick them on there.

1:30:05.840 --> 1:30:08.000
 They don't have the same lattice constant.

1:30:08.000 --> 1:30:10.360
 The spacing between atoms is different enough

1:30:10.360 --> 1:30:11.680
 that it just doesn't work.

1:30:11.680 --> 1:30:14.880
 So nature does not seem to be telling us

1:30:14.880 --> 1:30:17.960
 that, hey, go ahead and combine light sources

1:30:17.960 --> 1:30:19.960
 with your digital switches

1:30:19.960 --> 1:30:22.680
 for conventional digital computing.

1:30:22.680 --> 1:30:24.720
 And conventional digital computing

1:30:24.720 --> 1:30:27.680
 will often require smaller scale, I guess,

1:30:27.680 --> 1:30:29.600
 in terms of smartphone.

1:30:30.600 --> 1:30:35.440
 So in which kind of systems does nature hint

1:30:35.440 --> 1:30:40.440
 that we can use light and photons for communication?

1:30:41.120 --> 1:30:43.560
 Well, so let me just try and be clear.

1:30:43.560 --> 1:30:46.840
 You can use light for communication in digital systems.

1:30:46.840 --> 1:30:50.280
 Just the light sources are not intimately integrated

1:30:50.280 --> 1:30:51.120
 with the silicon.

1:30:51.120 --> 1:30:52.640
 You manufacture all the silicon,

1:30:52.640 --> 1:30:55.280
 you have your microchip, plunk it down.

1:30:55.280 --> 1:30:57.240
 And then you manufacture your light sources,

1:30:57.240 --> 1:30:59.280
 separate chip, completely different process,

1:30:59.280 --> 1:31:01.000
 made in a different foundry,

1:31:01.000 --> 1:31:03.760
 and then you put those together at the package level.

1:31:03.760 --> 1:31:07.920
 So now you have some, I would say,

1:31:07.920 --> 1:31:10.040
 a great deal of architectural limitations

1:31:10.040 --> 1:31:15.040
 that are introduced by that sort of package level integration

1:31:15.920 --> 1:31:18.520
 as opposed to monolithic on the same chip integration,

1:31:18.520 --> 1:31:20.120
 but it's still a very useful thing to do.

1:31:20.120 --> 1:31:23.640
 And that's where I had done some work previously

1:31:23.640 --> 1:31:24.640
 before I came to NIST.

1:31:24.640 --> 1:31:28.440
 There's a project led by Vladimir Stojanovich

1:31:28.440 --> 1:31:31.360
 that now spun out into a company called IR Labs,

1:31:31.360 --> 1:31:33.720
 led by Mark Wade and Chen Sun,

1:31:33.720 --> 1:31:35.000
 where they're doing exactly that.

1:31:35.000 --> 1:31:36.960
 So you have your light source chip,

1:31:36.960 --> 1:31:39.760
 your silicon chip, whatever it may be doing,

1:31:39.760 --> 1:31:40.880
 maybe it's digital electronics,

1:31:40.880 --> 1:31:43.640
 maybe it's some other control purpose, something.

1:31:43.640 --> 1:31:47.760
 And the silicon chip drives the light source chip

1:31:47.760 --> 1:31:49.760
 and modulates the intensity of the light,

1:31:49.760 --> 1:31:52.640
 so you can get data out of the package on an optical fiber.

1:31:52.640 --> 1:31:56.560
 And that still gives you tremendous advantages in bandwidth,

1:31:56.560 --> 1:31:58.840
 as opposed to sending those signals out

1:31:58.840 --> 1:32:00.760
 over electrical lines,

1:32:00.760 --> 1:32:05.160
 but it is somewhat peculiar to my eye

1:32:05.160 --> 1:32:07.880
 that they have to be integrated at this package level.

1:32:07.880 --> 1:32:09.760
 And those people, I mean, they're so smart.

1:32:09.760 --> 1:32:12.880
 Those are my colleagues that I respect a great deal.

1:32:12.880 --> 1:32:15.520
 So it's very clear that it's not just

1:32:16.760 --> 1:32:18.760
 they're making a bad choice.

1:32:18.760 --> 1:32:20.480
 This is what physics is telling us.

1:32:20.480 --> 1:32:22.280
 It just wouldn't make any sense

1:32:22.280 --> 1:32:24.240
 to try to stick them together.

1:32:24.240 --> 1:32:26.480
 Yeah, so even if it's difficult,

1:32:28.160 --> 1:32:30.880
 it's easier than the alternative, unfortunately.

1:32:30.880 --> 1:32:31.720
 I think so, yes.

1:32:31.720 --> 1:32:33.280
 And again, I need to go back

1:32:33.280 --> 1:32:35.080
 and make sure that I've not taken the wrong way.

1:32:35.080 --> 1:32:37.960
 I'm not saying that the pursuit of integrating compound

1:32:37.960 --> 1:32:40.040
 semiconductors with silicon is fruitless

1:32:40.040 --> 1:32:41.120
 and shouldn't be pursued.

1:32:41.120 --> 1:32:43.400
 It should, and people are doing great work.

1:32:43.400 --> 1:32:45.680
 Kai Mei Lao and John Bauer's others,

1:32:45.680 --> 1:32:48.200
 they're doing it and they're making progress.

1:32:48.200 --> 1:32:50.480
 But to my eye, it doesn't look like

1:32:50.480 --> 1:32:55.480
 that's ever going to be just the standard monolithic

1:32:57.120 --> 1:32:58.560
 light source on silicon process.

1:32:58.560 --> 1:33:00.000
 I just don't see it.

1:33:00.000 --> 1:33:02.800
 Yeah, so nature kinda points the way, usually.

1:33:02.800 --> 1:33:04.080
 And if you resist nature,

1:33:04.080 --> 1:33:05.640
 you're gonna have to do a lot more work.

1:33:05.640 --> 1:33:07.680
 And it's gonna be expensive and not scalable.

1:33:07.680 --> 1:33:08.520
 Got it.

1:33:08.520 --> 1:33:11.280
 Okay, so let's go far into the future.

1:33:11.280 --> 1:33:14.720
 Let's imagine this gigantic neuromorphic computing system

1:33:14.720 --> 1:33:17.320
 that simulates all of our realities

1:33:17.320 --> 1:33:19.040
 that currently is Metro Matrix 4.

1:33:19.040 --> 1:33:23.160
 So this thing, this powerful computer,

1:33:23.160 --> 1:33:24.880
 how does it operate?

1:33:24.880 --> 1:33:27.480
 So what are the neurons?

1:33:27.480 --> 1:33:29.000
 What is the communication?

1:33:29.000 --> 1:33:29.960
 What's your sense?

1:33:29.960 --> 1:33:34.160
 All right, so let me now, after spending 45 minutes

1:33:34.160 --> 1:33:36.120
 trashing light source integration with silicon,

1:33:36.120 --> 1:33:40.080
 let me now say why I'm basing my entire life,

1:33:40.080 --> 1:33:43.640
 professional life on integrating light sources

1:33:43.640 --> 1:33:44.920
 with electronics.

1:33:44.920 --> 1:33:47.000
 I think the game is completely different

1:33:47.000 --> 1:33:49.560
 when you're talking about superconducting electronics.

1:33:49.560 --> 1:33:54.200
 For several reasons, let me try to go through them.

1:33:54.200 --> 1:33:56.440
 One is that, as I mentioned,

1:33:56.440 --> 1:33:58.560
 it's difficult to integrate those compounds

1:33:58.560 --> 1:34:01.320
 and semiconductor light sources with silicon.

1:34:01.320 --> 1:34:04.840
 With silicon is a requirement that is introduced

1:34:04.840 --> 1:34:07.320
 by the fact that using semiconducting electronics.

1:34:07.320 --> 1:34:08.880
 In superconducting electronics,

1:34:08.880 --> 1:34:10.880
 you're still gonna start with a silicon wafer,

1:34:10.880 --> 1:34:13.080
 but it's just the bread for your sandwich

1:34:13.080 --> 1:34:13.920
 in a lot of ways.

1:34:13.920 --> 1:34:15.840
 You're not using that silicon

1:34:15.840 --> 1:34:17.760
 in precisely the same way for the electronics.

1:34:17.760 --> 1:34:20.480
 You're now depositing superconducting materials

1:34:20.480 --> 1:34:21.880
 on top of that.

1:34:21.880 --> 1:34:24.560
 The prospects for integrating light sources

1:34:24.560 --> 1:34:27.440
 with that kind of an electronic process

1:34:27.440 --> 1:34:30.480
 are certainly less explored,

1:34:30.480 --> 1:34:31.960
 but I think much more promising

1:34:31.960 --> 1:34:34.280
 because you don't need those light sources

1:34:34.280 --> 1:34:36.600
 to be intimately integrated with the transistors.

1:34:36.600 --> 1:34:37.920
 That's where the problems come up.

1:34:37.920 --> 1:34:39.920
 They don't need to be lattice matched to the silicon,

1:34:39.920 --> 1:34:41.160
 all that kind of stuff.

1:34:41.160 --> 1:34:43.640
 Instead, it seems possible

1:34:43.640 --> 1:34:45.080
 that you can take those compounds,

1:34:45.080 --> 1:34:47.320
 semiconductor light sources,

1:34:47.320 --> 1:34:49.160
 stick them on the silicon wafer,

1:34:49.160 --> 1:34:51.400
 and then grow your superconducting electronics

1:34:51.400 --> 1:34:52.320
 on the top of that.

1:34:52.320 --> 1:34:55.800
 It's at least not obviously going to fail.

1:34:55.800 --> 1:34:57.320
 So the computation would be done

1:34:57.320 --> 1:35:00.160
 on the superconductive material as well?

1:35:00.160 --> 1:35:01.960
 Yes, the computation is done

1:35:01.960 --> 1:35:03.960
 in the superconducting electronics,

1:35:03.960 --> 1:35:06.440
 and the light sources receive signals

1:35:06.440 --> 1:35:08.240
 that say, hey, a neuron reach threshold,

1:35:08.240 --> 1:35:09.840
 produce a pulse of light,

1:35:09.840 --> 1:35:12.520
 send it out to all your downstream synaptic connections.

1:35:12.520 --> 1:35:16.280
 Those are again superconducting electronics,

1:35:16.280 --> 1:35:18.040
 perform your computation,

1:35:18.040 --> 1:35:19.680
 and you're off to the races.

1:35:19.680 --> 1:35:20.800
 Your network works.

1:35:20.800 --> 1:35:22.640
 So then if we can rewind real quick.

1:35:22.640 --> 1:35:26.000
 So what are the limitations of the challenges

1:35:26.000 --> 1:35:28.960
 of superconducting electronics

1:35:28.960 --> 1:35:31.520
 when we think about constructing these kinds of systems?

1:35:31.520 --> 1:35:35.680
 So actually, let me say one other thing

1:35:35.680 --> 1:35:37.600
 about the light sources,

1:35:37.600 --> 1:35:39.880
 and then I'll move on, I promise,

1:35:39.880 --> 1:35:42.360
 because this is probably tedious for some.

1:35:42.360 --> 1:35:44.040
 This is super exciting.

1:35:44.040 --> 1:35:45.760
 Okay, one other thing about the light sources,

1:35:45.760 --> 1:35:48.920
 I said that silicon is terrible at emitting photons.

1:35:48.920 --> 1:35:50.680
 It's just not what it's meant to do.

1:35:50.680 --> 1:35:52.840
 However, the game is different

1:35:52.840 --> 1:35:54.080
 when you're at low temperature.

1:35:54.080 --> 1:35:55.760
 If you're working with superconductors,

1:35:55.760 --> 1:35:57.000
 you have to be at low temperature

1:35:57.000 --> 1:35:58.720
 because they don't work otherwise.

1:35:58.720 --> 1:36:00.280
 When you're at four Kelvin,

1:36:00.280 --> 1:36:03.480
 silicon is not obviously a terrible light source.

1:36:03.480 --> 1:36:05.880
 It's still not as efficient as compound semiconductors,

1:36:05.880 --> 1:36:08.720
 but it might be good enough for this application.

1:36:08.720 --> 1:36:11.360
 The final thing that I'll mention about that is, again,

1:36:11.360 --> 1:36:14.000
 leveraging superconductors, as I said,

1:36:14.000 --> 1:36:15.440
 in a different context,

1:36:15.440 --> 1:36:19.560
 superconducting detectors can receive one single photon.

1:36:19.560 --> 1:36:21.280
 In that conversation, I failed to mention

1:36:21.280 --> 1:36:23.480
 that semiconductors can also receive photons.

1:36:23.480 --> 1:36:26.640
 That's the primary mechanism by which it's done.

1:36:26.640 --> 1:36:29.200
 A camera in your phone that's receptive to visible light

1:36:29.200 --> 1:36:31.120
 is receiving photons.

1:36:31.120 --> 1:36:32.240
 It's based on silicon,

1:36:32.240 --> 1:36:34.400
 or you can make it in different semiconductors

1:36:34.400 --> 1:36:36.600
 for different wavelengths,

1:36:36.600 --> 1:36:39.640
 but it requires, on the order of a thousand,

1:36:39.640 --> 1:36:43.600
 a few thousand photons to receive a pulse.

1:36:43.600 --> 1:36:46.200
 Now, when you're using a superconducting detector,

1:36:46.200 --> 1:36:48.400
 you need one photon, exactly one.

1:36:48.400 --> 1:36:50.920
 I mean, one or more.

1:36:50.920 --> 1:36:54.880
 So the fact that your synopsis can now be based

1:36:54.880 --> 1:36:56.720
 on superconducting detectors,

1:36:56.720 --> 1:36:58.840
 instead of semiconducting detectors,

1:36:58.840 --> 1:37:00.760
 brings the light levels that are required

1:37:00.760 --> 1:37:03.200
 down by some three orders of magnitude.

1:37:03.200 --> 1:37:06.560
 So now you don't need good light sources.

1:37:06.560 --> 1:37:08.840
 You can have the world's worst light sources

1:37:08.840 --> 1:37:11.880
 as long as they spit out maybe a few thousand photons

1:37:11.880 --> 1:37:13.840
 every time a neuron fires.

1:37:13.840 --> 1:37:17.680
 You have the hardware principles in place

1:37:17.680 --> 1:37:19.640
 that you might be able to perform

1:37:19.640 --> 1:37:21.720
 this optoelectronic integration.

1:37:21.720 --> 1:37:23.640
 To me, optoelectronic integration is,

1:37:23.640 --> 1:37:25.040
 it's just so enticing.

1:37:25.040 --> 1:37:27.640
 We want to be able to leverage electronics

1:37:27.640 --> 1:37:30.400
 for computation, light for communication,

1:37:30.400 --> 1:37:32.120
 working with silicon microelectronics

1:37:32.120 --> 1:37:35.040
 at room temperature that has been exceedingly difficult.

1:37:35.040 --> 1:37:40.040
 And I hope that when we move to the superconducting domain,

1:37:40.040 --> 1:37:41.880
 target a different application space

1:37:41.880 --> 1:37:44.960
 that is neuromorphic instead of digital,

1:37:44.960 --> 1:37:47.720
 and use superconducting detectors,

1:37:47.720 --> 1:37:50.160
 maybe optoelectronic integration comes to us.

1:37:50.160 --> 1:37:51.720
 Okay, so there's a bunch of questions.

1:37:51.720 --> 1:37:53.720
 So one is temperature.

1:37:53.720 --> 1:37:58.360
 So in these kind of hybrid heterogeneous systems,

1:37:58.360 --> 1:37:59.600
 what's the temperature?

1:37:59.600 --> 1:38:01.640
 What are some of the constraints of the operation here?

1:38:01.640 --> 1:38:03.640
 Does it all have to be at four Kelvin as well?

1:38:03.640 --> 1:38:06.880
 Four Kelvin, everything has to be at four Kelvin.

1:38:06.880 --> 1:38:09.760
 Okay, so what are the other engineering challenges

1:38:09.760 --> 1:38:14.360
 of making this kind of optoelectronic systems?

