 I mean number of interconnected neurons,

1:50:49.840 --> 1:50:51.760
 you absolutely have to be using

1:50:51.760 --> 1:50:53.640
 the third spatial dimension.

1:50:53.640 --> 1:50:55.960
 And that means on the wafer,

1:50:55.960 --> 1:50:57.360
 you need multiple layers

1:50:57.360 --> 1:50:59.600
 of both active and passive components.

1:50:59.600 --> 1:51:03.360
 Active, I mean superconducting electronic circuits

1:51:03.360 --> 1:51:05.360
 that are performing computations.

1:51:05.360 --> 1:51:07.400
 And passive, I mean these waveguides

1:51:07.400 --> 1:51:10.160
 that are routing the optical signals to different places,

1:51:10.160 --> 1:51:11.720
 you have to be able to stack those.

1:51:11.720 --> 1:51:15.240
 If you can get to something like 10 planes of each of those,

1:51:15.240 --> 1:51:18.840
 or maybe not even 10, maybe five, six, something like that,

1:51:18.840 --> 1:51:19.760
 then you're in business.

1:51:19.760 --> 1:51:22.880
 Now you can get millions of neurons on a wafer,

1:51:22.880 --> 1:51:26.360
 but that's not anywhere close to the brain scale.

1:51:26.360 --> 1:51:27.960
 In order to get to the scale of the human brain,

1:51:27.960 --> 1:51:30.000
 you're gonna have to also use the third dimension

1:51:30.000 --> 1:51:33.320
 in the sense that entire wafers need to be stacked

1:51:33.320 --> 1:51:34.160
 on top of each other

1:51:34.160 --> 1:51:36.080
 with fiber optic communication between them.

1:51:36.080 --> 1:51:38.640
 And we need to be able to fill a space

1:51:38.640 --> 1:51:42.040
 the size of this table with stacked wafers.

1:51:42.040 --> 1:51:44.280
 And that's when you can get to some 10 billion neurons

1:51:44.280 --> 1:51:45.120
 like your human brain.

1:51:45.120 --> 1:51:46.680
 And I don't think that's specific

1:51:46.680 --> 1:51:48.800
 to the optoelectronic approach that we're taking.

1:51:48.800 --> 1:51:51.400
 I think that applies to any hardware

1:51:51.400 --> 1:51:53.560
 where you're trying to reach commensurate scale

1:51:53.560 --> 1:51:55.000
 and complexity as the human brain.

1:51:55.000 --> 1:51:57.520
 So you need that fractal stacking.

1:51:57.520 --> 1:52:01.120
 So stacking on the wafer and stacking of the wafers

1:52:01.120 --> 1:52:03.240
 and then whatever the system,

1:52:03.240 --> 1:52:06.360
 the stacking of the tables with the wafers.

1:52:06.360 --> 1:52:07.680
 And it has to be fractal all the way.

1:52:07.680 --> 1:52:08.560
 You're exactly right.

1:52:08.560 --> 1:52:10.040
 Because that's the only way

1:52:10.040 --> 1:52:12.480
 that you can efficiently get information

1:52:12.480 --> 1:52:15.040
 from a small point to across that whole network.

1:52:15.040 --> 1:52:17.480
 It has to have the power law connected.

1:52:17.480 --> 1:52:20.600
 And photons out like optics throughout.

1:52:20.600 --> 1:52:21.440
 Yeah, absolutely.

1:52:21.440 --> 1:52:23.680
 Once you're at this scale, to me it's just obvious.

1:52:23.680 --> 1:52:25.560
 Of course you're using light for communication.

1:52:25.560 --> 1:52:30.560
 You have fiber optics given to us from nature, so simple.

1:52:30.560 --> 1:52:32.680
 The thought of even trying to do this,

1:52:32.680 --> 1:52:36.040
 any kind of electrical communication just doesn't,

1:52:36.040 --> 1:52:37.040
 it doesn't make sense to me.

1:52:37.040 --> 1:52:38.240
 I'm not saying it's wrong.

1:52:38.240 --> 1:52:40.840
 I don't know, but that's where I'm coming from.

1:52:40.840 --> 1:52:43.680
 So let's return to loop neurons.

1:52:43.680 --> 1:52:46.240
 Why are they called loop neurons?

1:52:46.240 --> 1:52:48.840
 Yeah, the term loop neurons comes from the fact,

1:52:48.840 --> 1:52:49.840
 like we've been talking about,

1:52:49.840 --> 1:52:53.240
 that they rely heavily on these superconducting loops.

1:52:53.240 --> 1:52:57.240
 So even in a lot of forms of digital computing

1:52:57.240 --> 1:53:01.360
 with superconductors, storing a signal

1:53:01.360 --> 1:53:05.280
 in a superconducting loop is a primary technique.

1:53:05.280 --> 1:53:08.840
 In this particular case, it's just loops everywhere you look.

1:53:08.840 --> 1:53:11.840
 So the strength of a synaptic weight

1:53:11.840 --> 1:53:15.280
 is gonna be set by the amount of current circulating

1:53:15.280 --> 1:53:17.960
 in a loop that is coupled to the synapse.

1:53:17.960 --> 1:53:22.960
 So memory is implemented as current circulating

1:53:22.760 --> 1:53:24.360
 in a superconducting loop.

1:53:24.360 --> 1:53:28.000
 The coupling between say a synapse in a dendrite

1:53:28.000 --> 1:53:30.520
 or a synapse in the neuron cell body occurs

1:53:30.520 --> 1:53:33.920
 through loop coupling through transformer.

1:53:33.920 --> 1:53:35.600
 So current circulating in a synapse

1:53:35.600 --> 1:53:38.360
 is gonna induce current in a different loop,

1:53:38.360 --> 1:53:41.560
 a receiving loop in the neuron cell body.

1:53:41.560 --> 1:53:45.240
 So since all of the computation is happening

1:53:45.240 --> 1:53:47.360
 in these flux storage loops

1:53:47.360 --> 1:53:49.160
 and they play such a central role

1:53:49.160 --> 1:53:51.040
 in how the information is processed,

1:53:51.040 --> 1:53:53.600
 how memories are formed, all that stuff,

1:53:53.600 --> 1:53:54.800
 I didn't think too much about it.

1:53:54.800 --> 1:53:56.320
 I just called them loop neurons

1:53:56.320 --> 1:53:58.240
 because it rolls off the tongue a little bit better

1:53:58.240 --> 1:54:01.240
 than superconducting optoelectronic neurons.

1:54:02.240 --> 1:54:07.240
 Okay, so how do you design circuits for these loop neurons?

1:54:08.600 --> 1:54:09.760
 That's a great question.

1:54:09.760 --> 1:54:12.360
 There's a lot of different scales of design.

1:54:12.360 --> 1:54:16.400
 So at the level of just one synapse,

1:54:16.400 --> 1:54:19.040
 you can use conventional methods.

1:54:19.040 --> 1:54:21.400
 They're not that complicated

1:54:21.400 --> 1:54:23.240
 as far as superconducting electronics goes.

1:54:23.240 --> 1:54:27.120
 It's just for Joseph's injunctions or something like that,

1:54:27.120 --> 1:54:29.200
 depending on how much complexity you wanna add.

1:54:29.200 --> 1:54:34.200
 So you can just directly simulate each component in SPICE.

1:54:34.600 --> 1:54:35.880
 We've been with... What's SPICE?

1:54:35.880 --> 1:54:39.240
 It's Standard Electrical Simulation Software, basically.

1:54:39.240 --> 1:54:42.600
 So you're just explicitly solving the differential equations

1:54:42.600 --> 1:54:44.360
 that describe the circuit elements.

1:54:44.360 --> 1:54:46.240
 And then you can stack these things together

1:54:46.240 --> 1:54:48.880
 in that simulation software to then build circuits.

1:54:48.880 --> 1:54:51.600
 You can, but that becomes computationally expensive.

1:54:51.600 --> 1:54:54.120
 So one of the things when COVID hit,

1:54:54.120 --> 1:54:58.320
 we knew we had to turn some attention to more things you can do

1:54:58.320 --> 1:54:59.840
 at home in your basement or whatever.

1:54:59.840 --> 1:55:02.720
 And one of them was computational modeling.

1:55:02.720 --> 1:55:07.720
 So we started working on adapting,

1:55:07.800 --> 1:55:10.200
 abstracting out the circuit performance

1:55:10.200 --> 1:55:12.560
 so that you don't have to explicitly solve

1:55:12.560 --> 1:55:14.160
 the circuit equations,

1:55:14.160 --> 1:55:15.880
 which for Joseph's injunctions,

1:55:15.880 --> 1:55:18.480
 usually needs to be done on like a picosecond time scale

1:55:18.480 --> 1:55:21.240
 and you have a lot of nodes in your circuit.

1:55:21.240 --> 1:55:24.880
 So it results in a lot of differential equations

1:55:24.880 --> 1:55:26.360
 that need to be solved simultaneously.

1:55:26.360 --> 1:55:29.440
 We were looking for a way to simulate these circuits

1:55:29.440 --> 1:55:33.200
 that is scalable up to networks of millions or so.

1:55:33.200 --> 1:55:36.640
 Neurons is sort of where we're targeting right now.

1:55:36.640 --> 1:55:40.800
 So we were able to analyze the behavior of these circuits.

1:55:40.800 --> 1:55:43.640
 And as I said, it's based on these simple building blocks.

1:55:43.640 --> 1:55:46.360
 So you really only need to understand this one building block.

1:55:46.360 --> 1:55:49.000
 And if you get a good model of that, boom, it tiles.

1:55:49.000 --> 1:55:51.160
 And you can change the parameters in there

1:55:51.160 --> 1:55:52.840
 to get different behaviors and stuff.

1:55:52.840 --> 1:55:54.400
 But it's all based on now,

1:55:54.400 --> 1:55:57.120
 it's one differential equation that you need to solve.

1:55:57.120 --> 1:55:59.760
 So one differential equation

1:55:59.760 --> 1:56:03.760
 for every Synapse, Dendrite or Neuron in your system.

1:56:03.760 --> 1:56:05.360
 And for the neuroscientists out there,

1:56:05.360 --> 1:56:08.440
 it's just a simple leaky integrate and fire model.

1:56:08.440 --> 1:56:10.000
 Leaky integrator, basically.

1:56:10.000 --> 1:56:11.880
 A Synapse is a leaky integrator,

1:56:11.880 --> 1:56:13.480
 a Dendrite is a leaky integrator.

1:56:13.480 --> 1:56:18.480
 So I'm really fascinated by how this one simple component

1:56:18.480 --> 1:56:22.200
 can be used to achieve lots of different types

1:56:22.200 --> 1:56:24.440
 of dynamical activity.

1:56:24.440 --> 1:56:27.520
 And to me, that's where scalability comes from.

1:56:27.520 --> 1:56:29.200
 And also complexity as well.

1:56:29.200 --> 1:56:30.880
 Complexity is often characterized

1:56:30.880 --> 1:56:35.440
 by relatively simple building blocks

1:56:35.440 --> 1:56:39.360
 connected in potentially simple or sometimes complicated ways.

1:56:39.360 --> 1:56:41.040
 And then emergent new behavior

1:56:41.040 --> 1:56:44.680
 that was hard to predict from those simple elements.

1:56:44.680 --> 1:56:46.640
 And that's exactly what we're working with here.

1:56:46.640 --> 1:56:49.040
 So it's a very exciting platform,

1:56:49.040 --> 1:56:50.360
 both from a modeling perspective

1:56:50.360 --> 1:56:52.760
 and from a hardware manifestation perspective

1:56:52.760 --> 1:56:57.360
 where we can hopefully start to have this test bed

1:56:57.360 --> 1:56:58.840
 where we can explore things,

1:56:58.840 --> 1:57:00.800
 not just related to neuroscience,

1:57:00.800 --> 1:57:04.480
 but also related to other things that connected

1:57:04.480 --> 1:57:07.120
 to other physics like critical phenomenon,

1:57:07.120 --> 1:57:08.680
 ising models, things like that.

1:57:08.680 --> 1:57:13.080
 So you were asking how we simulate these circuits.

1:57:13.080 --> 1:57:14.560
 It's at different levels.

1:57:14.560 --> 1:57:18.360
 And we've got the simple spice circuit stuff.

1:57:18.360 --> 1:57:19.560
 That's no problem.

1:57:19.560 --> 1:57:21.760
 And now we're building these network models

1:57:21.760 --> 1:57:23.640
 based on this more efficient leaky integrator.

1:57:23.640 --> 1:57:26.240
 So we can actually reduce every element

1:57:26.240 --> 1:57:27.480
 to one differential equation.

1:57:27.480 --> 1:57:28.880
 And then we can also step through it

1:57:28.880 --> 1:57:30.720
 on a much coarser time grid.

1:57:30.720 --> 1:57:32.400
 So it ends up being something like a factor

1:57:32.400 --> 1:57:35.400
 of 1,000 to 10,000 speed improvement,

1:57:35.400 --> 1:57:37.800
 which allows us to simulate,

1:57:37.800 --> 1:57:40.560
 but hopefully up to millions of neurons.

1:57:40.560 --> 1:57:44.680
 Whereas before we would have been limited to tens,

1:57:44.680 --> 1:57:45.840
 a hundred, something like that.

1:57:45.840 --> 1:57:48.840
 And just like simulating quantum mechanical systems

1:57:48.840 --> 1:57:49.920
 with a quantum computer.

1:57:49.920 --> 1:57:53.440
 So the goal here is to understand such systems.

