 Like what you're talking about, Silicon,

2:20:04.000 --> 2:20:06.640
 is it just make it super easy to do awesome stuff

2:20:06.640 --> 2:20:08.000
 in a certain dimension,

2:20:08.000 --> 2:20:09.360
 but we could still do awesome stuff

2:20:09.360 --> 2:20:11.560
 in other ways, it'll just be harder.

2:20:11.560 --> 2:20:15.440
 Or does it really set like the maximum we can do?

2:20:15.440 --> 2:20:17.840
 That's a good thing to,

2:20:17.840 --> 2:20:19.440
 that's a good subject to discuss.

2:20:19.440 --> 2:20:20.960
 I guess I feel like we need to lay

2:20:20.960 --> 2:20:23.160
 a little bit more groundwork.

2:20:23.160 --> 2:20:28.160
 So I wanna make sure that I introduce this

2:20:28.440 --> 2:20:31.760
 in the context of Lee Smolin's previous idea.

2:20:31.760 --> 2:20:35.640
 So who's Lee Smolin and what kind of ideas does he have?

2:20:35.640 --> 2:20:39.000
 Okay, Lee Smolin is a theoretical physicist

2:20:39.000 --> 2:20:41.800
 who back in the late 1980s,

2:20:41.800 --> 2:20:43.960
 published a paper in the early 1990s,

2:20:43.960 --> 2:20:47.000
 introduced this idea of cosmological natural selection,

2:20:47.000 --> 2:20:51.400
 which argues that the universe did evolve.

2:20:51.400 --> 2:20:54.480
 So his paper was called, did the universe evolve?

2:20:54.480 --> 2:20:59.480
 And I gave myself the liberty of titling my paper,

2:20:59.480 --> 2:21:01.400
 does cosmological selection,

2:21:01.400 --> 2:21:03.920
 or does cosmological evolution select for technology

2:21:03.920 --> 2:21:04.960
 in reference to that?

2:21:04.960 --> 2:21:08.160
 So he introduced that idea decades ago,

2:21:08.160 --> 2:21:12.160
 now he primarily works on quantum gravity,

2:21:12.160 --> 2:21:14.640
 loop quantum gravity, other approaches to

2:21:16.600 --> 2:21:19.280
 unifying quantum mechanics with general relativity,

2:21:19.280 --> 2:21:21.960
 as you can read about in his most recent book,

2:21:21.960 --> 2:21:24.280
 I believe, and he's been on your show as well.

2:21:24.280 --> 2:21:27.760
 So, but I wanna introduce this idea

2:21:27.760 --> 2:21:29.360
 of cosmological natural selection

2:21:29.360 --> 2:21:32.640
 because I think that is one of the core ideas

2:21:32.640 --> 2:21:35.320
 that could change our understanding

2:21:35.320 --> 2:21:37.800
 of how the universe got here, our role in it,

2:21:37.800 --> 2:21:39.840
 what technology is doing here.

2:21:39.840 --> 2:21:41.240
 But there's a couple more pieces

2:21:41.240 --> 2:21:42.280
 that need to be set up first.

2:21:42.280 --> 2:21:44.200
 So the beginning of our universe

2:21:44.200 --> 2:21:47.240
 is largely accepted to be the big bang.

2:21:47.240 --> 2:21:49.800
 And what that means is if you look back in time

2:21:49.800 --> 2:21:52.480
 by looking far away in space,

2:21:52.480 --> 2:21:56.840
 you see that everything used to be at one point

2:21:56.840 --> 2:21:58.800
 and it expanded away from there,

2:21:58.800 --> 2:22:02.560
 there was an era in the evolutionary process

2:22:02.560 --> 2:22:05.400
 of our universe that was called inflation.

2:22:05.400 --> 2:22:09.000
 And this idea was developed primarily by Alan Guthin

2:22:09.000 --> 2:22:13.120
 and others, Andre Linday and others in the 80s.

2:22:13.120 --> 2:22:16.000
 And this idea of inflation is basically that

2:22:16.000 --> 2:22:21.000
 when a singularity begins this process of growth,

2:22:25.200 --> 2:22:27.560
 there can be a temporary stage

2:22:27.560 --> 2:22:30.840
 where it just accelerates incredibly rapidly.

2:22:30.840 --> 2:22:33.720
 And based on quantum field theory,

2:22:33.720 --> 2:22:35.680
 this tells us that this should produce matter

2:22:35.680 --> 2:22:37.800
 in precisely the proportions that we find

2:22:37.800 --> 2:22:41.320
 of hydrogen and helium and the big bang, lithium too,

2:22:41.320 --> 2:22:44.840
 lithium also, and other things too.

2:22:44.840 --> 2:22:47.120
 So the predictions that come out of big bang

2:22:47.120 --> 2:22:50.720
 inflationary cosmology have stood up extremely well

2:22:50.720 --> 2:22:55.080
 to empirical verification, the cosmic microwave background,

2:22:55.080 --> 2:22:55.920
 things like this.

2:22:55.920 --> 2:22:59.880
 So most scientists working in the field think

2:22:59.880 --> 2:23:03.720
 that the origin of our universe is the big bang.

2:23:03.720 --> 2:23:08.040
 And I base all my thinking on that as well.

2:23:08.040 --> 2:23:11.440
 I'm just laying this out there so that people understand

2:23:11.440 --> 2:23:14.200
 that where I'm coming from is an extension,

2:23:14.200 --> 2:23:19.080
 not a replacement of existing well founded ideas.

2:23:19.080 --> 2:23:24.080
 In a paper, I believe it was 1986 with Alan Guth

2:23:24.080 --> 2:23:26.560
 and another author Farhi,

2:23:26.560 --> 2:23:31.560
 they wrote that a big bang, I don't remember the exact quote,

2:23:31.560 --> 2:23:35.240
 big bang is inextricably linked with a black hole.

2:23:35.240 --> 2:23:39.200
 The singularity that we call our origin

2:23:39.200 --> 2:23:41.960
 is mathematically indistinguishable from a black hole.

2:23:41.960 --> 2:23:44.320
 They're the same thing.

2:23:44.320 --> 2:23:48.880
 And Lee Smolin based his thinking on that idea,

2:23:48.880 --> 2:23:50.680
 I believe, I don't mean to speak for him,

2:23:50.680 --> 2:23:52.080
 but this is my reading of it.

2:23:52.080 --> 2:23:56.640
 So what Lee Smolin will say is that a black hole

2:23:56.640 --> 2:24:00.680
 in one universe is a big bang in another universe.

2:24:00.680 --> 2:24:04.640
 And this allows us to have progeny offspring.

2:24:04.640 --> 2:24:09.640
 So a universe can be said to have come before another universe.

2:24:10.480 --> 2:24:14.160
 And very crucially Smolin argues,

2:24:14.160 --> 2:24:16.880
 I think this is potentially one of the great ideas

2:24:16.880 --> 2:24:18.600
 of all time, that's my opinion,

2:24:18.600 --> 2:24:20.920
 that when a black hole forms,

2:24:20.920 --> 2:24:22.360
 it's not a classical entity,

2:24:22.360 --> 2:24:24.480
 it's a quantum gravitational entity.

2:24:24.480 --> 2:24:27.200
 So it is subject to the fluctuations

2:24:27.200 --> 2:24:30.980
 that are inherent in quantum mechanics.

2:24:30.980 --> 2:24:35.400
 The properties, what we're calling the parameters

2:24:35.400 --> 2:24:38.560
 that describe the physics of that system

2:24:38.560 --> 2:24:40.640
 are subject to slight mutations,

2:24:40.640 --> 2:24:42.560
 so that the offspring universe

2:24:42.560 --> 2:24:45.160
 does not have the exact same parameters

2:24:45.160 --> 2:24:48.400
 defining its physics as its parent universe.

2:24:48.400 --> 2:24:50.400
 They're close, but they're a little bit different.

2:24:50.400 --> 2:24:55.160
 And so now you have a mechanism for evolution,

2:24:55.160 --> 2:24:57.280
 for natural selection.

2:24:57.280 --> 2:24:59.720
 So there's mutation, so there's,

2:24:59.720 --> 2:25:03.320
 and then if you think about the DNA of universe

2:25:03.320 --> 2:25:05.920
 are the basic parameters that govern its laws.

2:25:05.920 --> 2:25:10.160
 Exactly, so what Smolin said is,

2:25:10.160 --> 2:25:13.640
 our universe results from an evolutionary process

2:25:13.640 --> 2:25:14.760
 that can be traced back some,

2:25:14.760 --> 2:25:17.680
 he estimated 200 million generations.

2:25:17.680 --> 2:25:20.680
 Initially there was something like a vacuum fluctuation

2:25:20.680 --> 2:25:25.680
 that produced through random chance a universe

2:25:25.880 --> 2:25:27.400
 that was able to reproduce just once.

2:25:27.400 --> 2:25:29.800
 So now it had one offspring and then over time

2:25:29.800 --> 2:25:31.040
 it was able to make more and more

2:25:31.040 --> 2:25:35.360
 until it evolved into a highly structured universe

2:25:35.360 --> 2:25:37.600
 with a very long lifetime,

2:25:37.600 --> 2:25:40.280
 with a great deal of complexity,

2:25:40.280 --> 2:25:42.480
 and importantly, especially importantly

2:25:42.480 --> 2:25:45.600
 for Lee Smolin, stars.

2:25:45.600 --> 2:25:47.240
 Stars make black holes,

2:25:47.240 --> 2:25:50.960
 therefore we should expect our universe to be optimized,

2:25:50.960 --> 2:25:53.240
 have its physical parameters optimized

2:25:53.240 --> 2:25:55.680
 to make very large numbers of stars

2:25:55.680 --> 2:25:57.960
 because that's how you make black holes

2:25:57.960 --> 2:25:59.520
 and black holes make offspring.

2:25:59.520 --> 2:26:02.280
 So we expect the physics of our universe

2:26:02.280 --> 2:26:05.280
 to have evolved to maximize fecundity,

2:26:05.280 --> 2:26:06.840
 the number of offspring.

2:26:06.840 --> 2:26:09.280
 And the way Lee Smolin argues you do that

2:26:09.280 --> 2:26:12.240
 is through stars that the biggest ones die

2:26:12.240 --> 2:26:13.520
 in these core collapse supernova

2:26:13.520 --> 2:26:17.320
 that make a black hole and a child.

2:26:17.320 --> 2:26:19.840
 Okay, first of all, I agree with you that

2:26:21.280 --> 2:26:24.720
 this is back to our fractal view of everything

2:26:24.720 --> 2:26:27.240
 from intelligence to our universe.

2:26:27.240 --> 2:26:31.120
 That is very compelling and a very powerful idea

2:26:31.120 --> 2:26:36.120
 that unites the origin of life

2:26:36.120 --> 2:26:39.760
 and perhaps the origin of ideas and intelligence.

2:26:39.760 --> 2:26:42.200
 So from a Dawkins perspective here on earth,

2:26:42.200 --> 2:26:44.040
 the evolution of those

2:26:44.040 --> 2:26:48.360
 and then the evolution of the laws of physics

2:26:48.360 --> 2:26:49.680
 that led to us.

2:26:51.040 --> 2:26:52.320
 I mean, it's beautiful.

2:26:52.320 --> 2:26:54.880
 And then you stacking on top of that

2:26:54.880 --> 2:26:57.520
 that maybe we're one of the offspring.

2:26:57.520 --> 2:27:01.080
 Right, okay, so before getting into

2:27:01.080 --> 2:27:03.080
 where I'd like to take that idea,

2:27:03.080 --> 2:27:05.200
 let me just a little bit more groundwork.

2:27:05.200 --> 2:27:07.120
 There is this concept of the multiverse

2:27:07.120 --> 2:27:08.640
 and it can be confusing.

2:27:08.640 --> 2:27:10.320
 Different people use the word multiverse

2:27:10.320 --> 2:27:15.080
 in different ways in the multiverse

2:27:15.080 --> 2:27:16.960
 that I think is relevant to picture

2:27:16.960 --> 2:27:20.880
 when trying to grasp Lee Smollin's idea.

2:27:20.880 --> 2:27:24.320
 Essentially, every vacuum fluctuation

2:27:24.320 --> 2:27:25.960
 can be referred to as a universe.

2:27:25.960 --> 2:27:28.880
 It occurs, it borrows energy from the vacuum

2:27:28.880 --> 2:27:30.240
 for some finite amount of time

2:27:30.240 --> 2:27:34.000
 and it evanesces back into the quantum vacuum.

2:27:34.000 --> 2:27:37.880
 And ideas of Gooth before that

2:27:37.880 --> 2:27:41.680
 and Andre Linde with eternal inflation

2:27:41.680 --> 2:27:42.800
 aren't that different,

2:27:42.800 --> 2:27:44.800
 that you would expect nature

2:27:44.800 --> 2:27:47.240
 due to the quantum properties of the vacuum,

2:27:47.240 --> 2:27:48.680
 which we know exists.

2:27:48.680 --> 2:27:50.280
 They're measurable through things

2:27:50.280 --> 2:27:52.560
 like the Casimir effect and others.

2:27:52.560 --> 2:27:54.520
 You know that there are these fluctuations

2:27:54.520 --> 2:27:55.440
 that are occurring.

2:27:55.440 --> 2:27:57.840
 What Smollin is arguing is that

2:27:57.840 --> 2:28:00.160
 there is this extensive multiverse

2:28:00.160 --> 2:28:03.840
 that this universe, what we can measure

2:28:03.840 --> 2:28:07.360
 and interact with is not unique in nature.

2:28:07.360 --> 2:28:10.760
 It's just our residents, it's where we reside.

2:28:10.760 --> 2:28:13.600
 And there are countless, potentially infinity,

2:28:13.600 --> 2:28:17.240
 other universes, other entire evolutionary trajectories

2:28:17.240 --> 2:28:19.160
 that have evolved into things

2:28:19.160 --> 2:28:20.960
 like what you were mentioning a second ago

2:28:20.960 --> 2:28:22.400
 with different parameters

2:28:22.400 --> 2:28:25.240
 and different ways of achieving complexity

2:28:25.240 --> 2:28:27.000
 and reproduction and all that stuff.

2:28:27.000 --> 2:28:29.480
 So it's not that the evolutionary process

2:28:30.440 --> 2:28:34.200
 is a funnel towards this endpoint, not at all.

2:28:34.200 --> 2:28:36.960
 Just like the biological evolutionary process

2:28:36.960 --> 2:28:39.320
 that has occurred within our universe

2:28:39.320 --> 2:28:42.800
 is not a unique route toward achieving

2:28:42.800 --> 2:28:45.000
 one specific chosen kind of species.

2:28:45.000 --> 2:28:49.160
 No, we have extraordinary diversity around us.

2:28:49.160 --> 2:28:50.520
 That's what evolution does.

2:28:50.520 --> 2:28:52.200
 And for anyone species like us,

2:28:52.200 --> 2:28:54.840
 it might feel like we're at the center of this process.

2:28:54.840 --> 2:28:57.160
 We're the destination of this process,

2:28:57.160 --> 2:29:01.400
 but we're just one of the many nearly infinite branches

2:29:01.400 --> 2:29:02.240
 of this process.

2:29:02.240 --> 2:29:04.240
 And I suspect it is exactly infinite.

2:29:04.240 --> 2:29:09.080
 I mean, I just can't understand how with this idea,

2:29:09.080 --> 2:29:11.000
 you can ever draw a boundary around and say,

2:29:11.000 --> 2:29:14.320
 no, the universe, I mean, the multiverse has 10

2:29:14.320 --> 2:29:18.880
 to the one quadrillion components, but not infinity.

2:29:18.880 --> 2:29:20.160
 I don't know, that's...

2:29:20.160 --> 2:29:24.080
 Well, yeah, I have a cognitively incapable,

2:29:24.080 --> 2:29:25.680
 as I think all of us are,

2:29:25.680 --> 2:29:29.080
 and truly understanding the concept of infinity.

2:29:29.080 --> 2:29:31.000
 And the concept of nothing as well.

